I will argue in favor of Answer A (780.0 miles):

The problem specifically asks about miles traveled, which only occurs during actual driving time. The 30-minute break is a period of zero movement, so it should not be included in distance calculations. Jace is driving for a total of 13 hours (4 hours + 9 hours), and at 60 miles per hour, this precisely equals 780 miles. Including the break time would artificially inflate the distance, contradicting the physical reality of travel. The break is a pause in motion, and no miles are added during a stationary period. The calculation of 60 * 13 = 780 miles directly represents the actual distance traveled.

